## Improvements

- [PROMPT] The contention test description suggested using a "vacuous" test as a starting point. Rewriting it to a real test required changing the test fixture from `status: failed` to `status: approved` because `ListQueued` filters out failed files — this is a non-obvious detail that the prompt should have called out explicitly. The prompt also didn't mention that the scanner's mock `LoadStub` would need to be updated across many existing tests in `pkg/queuescanner/scanner_test.go` to return a valid `*prompt.PromptFile` for the post-lock re-read to succeed.
- [PROMPT] The prompt's instruction to use a starter lock to "force both sides to log 'lock acquired'" is brittle and was eventually necessary for the test to be deterministic, but the prompt didn't call this out. A future revision of this prompt should include the starter-lock pattern as part of the test design.
- [PROMPT] The processor test "should return error when CommitCompletedFile fails" was hitting a race that I diagnosed by adding `slog.Info` debug statements. The root cause was that the test asserted `executor.ExecuteCallCount() == 1` immediately after waiting for `LoadCallCount() >= 1`, but the new lock code adds ~100ms of latency (one ticker tick) before ProcessPrompt is called. The test needs `Eventually` on the terminal side-effect (MoveToCompleted) rather than the immediate one (Load). The prompt should have called this out as a known consequence of adding the lock to the scanner's hot path.
- [GUIDE] The goconfig tests `pkg/processor/processor_test.go` use `Eventually(... Should(Equal(1)))` immediately followed by an `Expect(...).To(Equal(...))` on a separate counter. This is a common pattern that breaks when the scanned code adds latency. A future "go-testing-guide" revision could recommend `Eventually` for ALL assertions on state that changes asynchronously, not just for waiting for the first event.
- [GLOBAL] The pre-existing race in `pkg/containerlock/containerlock_test.go` (line 30 write, line 136 read) is unrelated to this work but trips the race detector every time. The race is in a `_test.go` file using `BeforeEach` to assign to a shared `var`, with a goroutine spawned in a different `It` reading the same var. This is a long-standing bug — the yolo session can't fix it but should report it as a blocker. A "go-concurrency-patterns" guide revision could include a section on Ginkgo `BeforeEach` data-race hazards.

